==English==

===Etymology===
* First attested around 1325.
* From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|abounden|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|fro}} {{term|abonder|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|la}} {{term|abundare|abundāre|lang=la}}, present active infinitive of {{term|abundo|abundō|overflow|lang=la}}, which comes from {{term|ab||from, down from|lang=la}} + {{term|undo|undō|surge, swell, rise in waves|lang=la}}, from {{term|unda|wave|lang=la}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/əˈbaʊnd/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/əˈbaʊnd/}}
* {{audio|en-us-abound.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|aʊnd}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{context|intransitive|obsolete}} To be [[wealthy]].
# {{intransitive}} To be highly [[productive]].
# {{intransitive}} To be full to [[overflowing]]. 
# {{intransitive}} To be present or available in large numbers; to be plentiful
#: Wild animals '''abound''' wherever man does not stake his claim.
#* Where sin '''abounded''' grace did much more '''abound'''. ''Romans 5:20''.
# {{intransitive}} To be [[copiously]] supplied; 
#: ''The wilderness '''abounds''' in traps.''
#* The wild boar which '''abounds''' in some parts of the continent of Europe. - Chambers.

====Usage notes====
* {{sense|copiously supplied}} Abound is followed by ''in'' or ''with''.

